\title[]{ECB's Target claims and liabilities: A cause or a reflection of the current Euro crisis?}
\author[]{J\o rn Inge Halvorsen \inst{1}}
\institute[]{Norwegian Business School (BI)}
\date[]{28. September, 2012}
\maketitle
\section{Present situation}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Economics of Monetary Union}
\begin{itemize}
\item The policy debate about the Euro crisis seems mainly to be founded  on results  discussed in standard textbooks on the economics of monetary union (see for e.g. \cite{de2012economics}).
\begin{itemize}
\item Applies mainly a standard IS-LM model framework.
\item Poorly microfounded.
\item Relies on various shortcuts.
\end{itemize}
\item \cite{sinn2012target} interpet the euro crisis based on accounting data from the Target database. Their  analysis  raises a host of interesting questions in areas of:
\begin{itemize}
\item Democratic voting system within the Eurozone (one country one vote).\\
\item Risk redistribution among countrie and agents.
\item Legal issues.
\item Conventional and unconventional monetary policy tools.
\item \textbf{Markets vs. public policy of relaxed budget constraints.}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Sovereign debt}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{debtgdp.png}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Interest rate spreads}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{spread.png}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Sovereign debt and interest rate spreads}
\begin{itemize}
\item Is the Euro crisis purely a sovereign debt crisis?
\begin{itemize}
\item Before the U.S. financial crisis,   only Greece and Portugal had a public deficit to GDP ratio that exceeded three percent.   \end{itemize}
\item The P(I)IGS also suffer from severe external imbalances:\begin{itemize}
\item Intro of the Euro: \\
Capital import $\Rightarrow$ Credit driven boom cycle $\Rightarrow$ Misallocation of resources.
\item After the U.S. financial crisis:\\
Interbank market broke down. Reallocation of wealth portfolios.
\item Today:\\
Countries are too expansive. Need for  a price realignment. But so far few signs of any deflation?
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\section{Target claims and liabilities}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{The Balance of Payments}
\begin{itemize}
\item The BOP under different monetary policy regimes can be written as:
\begin{itemize}
\item Floating
\begin{equation*}
0 \equiv \text{CUR.ACC.} + \text{CAP.ACC.}
\end{equation*}
\item Fixed
\begin{equation*}
\Delta\text{RES.} \equiv \text{CUR.ACC.} + \text{CAP.ACC.}
\end{equation*}
\item Eurozone
\begin{equation*}
\Delta\text{TC} \equiv \text{CUR.ACC.} + \text{CAP.ACC.}
\end{equation*}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
Target claims (TC)  (liabilities) represent accumulated intra-Eurozone balance of payments surpluses (deficits).
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics{targetcl.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item  Target claims and liabilities
\begin{itemize}
\item Electronic interest rate bearing assets accumulated between the national central banks (NCBs) of the Eurozone.
\item Earn interest rate equal to the main refinancing rate of the ECB.
\item Without (unlike the federal reserve system in the U.S.) formal redemption possibilities.
\end{itemize}
\item System theoretically sustainable, but politically?
\item \cite{sinn2012target}: The Euro crisis is a balance of payment crisis.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\section{Bretton Woods as a parallel}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{}
\begin{itemize}
\item Bretton Woods System: Monetary agreement between U.S. and its allies after the second World war
\item Main ingredients:
\begin{itemize}
\item U.S. dollar fixed ratio towards gold.
\item Other countries currencies fixed their currencies toward dollar.
\item No direct regulations on money supply growth
\end{itemize}
\item First phase considered fairly successful.
\item External imbalances within the system from 1958.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
%\frametitle{ The process of outside money creation}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{balsheetbw.png}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{The collapse of the Bretton Woods system}
\begin{itemize}
\item The process of outside money helped to finance U.S. its huge current account deficit. 
\item Dollar reserves piling up in various NCBs.\\
$\Rightarrow$ no longer a credible claim on gold.
\item 1970-1971:
\begin{itemize}
\item De Gaule: threatend to redeem dollar reserves for gold.
\item Nixon : responded by making U.S. dollar no longer redeemable towards gold. 
\end{itemize}
\item 1971: End of Bretton Woods.

\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\section{Differences}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Major differences between the Bretton Woods system and the Eurozone}
\begin{itemize}
\item The  "currency ratio" is 1:1 between the countries.
\item Transactions today mainly electronical (Target 2-system).
\item Target claims are without formal redeemption possibilities.
\item ECB governing council in control over money base creation.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{BalSheetEZ.png}
\end{frame}
\section{Market interventions and TC}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Monetary policy interventions through the Target system}
\begin{itemize}
\item Note: With stable money demand and without money base creation, Target claims would be zero in all periods.
\item Consequently, Target 
\begin{itemize}
\item Conventional: Changes in the
\item Unconventional 
\end{itemize}
\item As such, we can write
\begin{equation*}
\text{CUR.ACC.} + \text{CAP.ACC.}\equiv \Delta\text{TC}
\end{equation*}
Target credit 
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Two special cases }
\begin{enumerate}
\item Electronic money base growth with capital market break down
\begin{equation*}
\text{CUR.ACC.} \equiv \Delta\text{TC}
\end{equation*}
$\Rightarrow $ Finances current account deficit. 
\item Electronic money base growth with current account in balance  \begin{equation*}
\text{CAP.ACC.} \equiv \Delta\text{TC}
\end{equation*}
$\Rightarrow $ Finances net capital outflow.
\end{enumerate}
For a country entering the bust phase of a credit driven business cycle, target credit either (1) postpone the necessary price realigment process or (2) transfer risk in the capital market or a combination of (1) and (2). \end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Monetary policy by the ECB after the U.S. financial crisis}
\begin{itemize}
\item From October 2008 to May 2009, ECB reduces its main refinancing rate from 4,25\% to 1 \%.
\item Full allotment policy (i.e. NCBs provide credit in any amount given sufficient collateral) 
\begin{center}
\includegraphics{ebc_creq.png} 
\end{center}
\item From 2011 the NBCs of Ireland and Greece started to provide  Emergency liquidity assistance (ELA) to their commercial bank. \end{itemize}


\end{frame}
\section{The case for the PIIGS economies}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{tc_ca_cu.png}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{}
